revision.text:
{{Infobox Cloud |name=Cirrus vertebratus |image location=Cirrus vertebratus.jpg |image name=Cirrus vertebratus cloud |abbreviation=Ci ve |symbol=CH_1.png |genus=Cirrus (''curl of hair'') |species=vertebratus (''like a spinal column'') |variety= |altitude_m=Above 6,000 |altitude_ft=Above 20,000 |appearance=looks like a spinal column or a fish skeleton<ref>{{cite web|title=Cirrus|url=http://www.clouds-online.com/cloud_atlas/cirrus/cirrus.htm|work=Cloud Atlas|accessdate=13 July 2011|author=Wolken Online}}</ref> |precipitation=No}} '''Cirrus vertebratus''' is a type of [[cirrus cloud]]. The name ''cirrus vertebratus'' is derived from [[Latin]], meaning "jointed, articulated, vertebrated".<ref>{{cite web|title=Definition of vertebratus|url=http://latinlexicon.org/definition.php?p1=2062674|accessdate=13 July 2011|author=Numen - The Latin Lexicon}}</ref> Like [[cirrus intortus]], the vertebratus species is exclusive to the cirrus genus.<ref>{{cite book|last=Dunlop|first=Storm|title=The weather identification handbook|year=2003|publisher=Lyons Press|location=Guilford, Conn.|isbn=1-58574-857-9|pages=58|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=BR2ft4G5TgQC&lpg=PA1&pg=PA58#v=onepage&q=vertebratus&f=false|edition=1st Lyons Press|accessdate=13 July 2011}}</ref> Cirrus vertebratus gives the impression of vertebrae in a spinal column, ribs, or a fish skeleton.<ref>{{cite web|last=Callanan|first=Martin|title=Cirrus vertebratus|url=http://nephology.eu/cirrus/cirrus-vertebratus|work=International Cloud Atlas|publisher=nephology.eu|accessdate=13 July 2011}}</ref>
The species is an unusual form of [[cirrus cloud]]s and is formed by air moving parallel to the main cloud line. The gaps in the cloud occur where air is descending, while the "ribs" of the cloud correspond with areas of uplift. Their occurrence appears to be connected with the location of the [[jet stream]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Cumulus Clouds|url=http://www.wolstanton.org.uk/public_html/web_weather/web/gallery_clouds_cirrus.php|work=Clouds|accessdate=13 July 2011|author=Wolstanton Weather|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120327014352/http://www.wolstanton.org.uk/public_html/web_weather/web/gallery_clouds_cirrus.php|archivedate=27 March 2013}}</ref>
==See also== *[[List of cloud types]]
