{{Infobox writer <!-- For more information see [[:Template:Infobox Writer/doc]]. --> | name = Kyle Boelte | pseudonym = | birth_name = | birth_date = | birth_place = Kansas, US | death_date = | death_place = | resting_place = | occupation = | language = [[English language|English]] | nationality = American | ethnicity = | citizenship = | education = | alma_mater = | period = | genre = Nonfiction | subject = | movement = | notableworks = ''The Beautiful Unseen'' | spouse = | partner = | children = | relatives = | influences = | influenced = | awards = | signature = | signature_alt = | website = {{URL|http://www.kyleboelte.com/}} | portaldisp = }} '''Kyle Boelte''' is an American essayist and author. He was born in a small town in western Kansas and grew up near Denver, Colorado.<ref>The Los Angeles Review of Books [http://lareviewofbooks.org/author/kyle-boelte Author Page for Kyle Boelte]</ref>
Boelte's book ''The Beautiful Unseen: Variations on Fog and Forgetting'' is about his brother's suicide, when they were both teenagers, as well as [[San Francisco fog]].<ref name="auto">[http://www.sfgate.com/books/article/The-Beautiful-Unseen-by-Kyle-Boelte-6076353.php 'The Beautiful Unseen,’ by Kyle Boelte], San Francisco Chronicle, 2/11/2015</ref> The book received positive reviews in The San Francisco Chronicle ("one of the most haunting books ever written about the fragility of memory"),<ref name="auto"/> The Los Angeles Review of Books ("Boelte’s sure-footed prose makes ''The Beautiful Unseen'' a lovely journey"),<ref>[http://lareviewofbooks.org/review/fog-chaser Fog Chaser], The Los Angeles Review of Books, 2/09/2015</ref> and Booklist ("Boelte conveys the deep, abiding sense of loss such tragedies inflict, yet softly, tenderly communicates the conflicting sensations of confronting memories, both lost and found").<ref>[http://www.booklistonline.com/The-Beautiful-Unseen-Variations-on-Fog-and-Forgetting-Kyle-Boelte/pid=7212283 Booklist Review], Booklist Online, 2/01/2015</ref> Its major themes include the impermanence of memory and the importance of nature, including wilderness, in our lives.<ref>[http://www.sierraclub.org/sierra/2015-1-january-february/green-life/how-nature-teaches-us-grieve How Nature Teaches Us to Grieve], Sierra, January/February 2015</ref>
Boelte's essays have been published in Zyzzyva,<ref>[http://www.zyzzyva.org/issue/volume-31-1-spring-2015/ Reluctant Citizens], Zyzzyva, Volume 31, #1, Spring 2015</ref> High Country News,<ref>[https://www.hcn.org/issues/47.2/half-blind-valley Half-Blind Valley], High Country News, 2/02/2015</ref> and Full Stop.<ref>[http://www.full-stop.net/2015/01/13/blog/kyle-boelte/tie-your-own-rope/ Tie Your Own Rope], Full Stop, 1/13/2015</ref> He was a finalist for the Annie Dillard Award for Creative Nonfiction in 2013.<ref>[http://bhreview.org/2013/06/07/announcing-2013-contest-winners/ Announcing 2013 Contest Winners], Bellingham Review, 6/07/2015</ref> His essay "Reluctant Citizens" was included in "The Best American Nonrequired Reading 2016" and was cited as a Notable Essay in "The Best American Essays 2016".
==Bibliography== Kyle Boelte (2015) ''The Beautiful Unseen: Variations on Fog and Forgetting''. Soft Skull Press. {{ISBN|978-1619024588}}
