[[Category:Panicum|*List]]
[[Category:Lists of plant species|Panicum]]

{{see also|List of mountains of Hawaii}}
{{see|Geography of Hawaii|Geology of Hawaii}}
[[File:KeckObservatory.jpg|thumb|260px|[[Mauna Kea]] on the [[Island of Hawaiʻi]] is the [[topographic elevation|highest]] [[summit (topography)|peak]] in the [[United States|U.S.]] [[Hawaii|State of Hawai{{okina}}i]] and the entire [[Pacific Ocean]].  Mauna Kea is the [[Mountain|tallest mountain]] on [[Earth]] as measured from base to summit.]]

This article comprises three sortable tables of the 13 [[Summit|major mountain peaks]]{{efn|This article defines a significant summit as a summit with at least {{convert|100|m|1|abbr=off|comma=5|sp=us}} of [[topographic prominence]], and a major summit as a summit with at least {{convert|500|m|0|abbr=off|comma=5|sp=us}} of topographic prominence.  An [[Ultra-prominent peak|ultra-prominent summit]] is a summit with at least {{convert|1500|m|0|abbr=off|comma=5|sp=us}} of topographic prominence.}} of the [[Hawaiian Islands]] and the [[United States|U.S.]] [[Hawaii|State of Hawai{{okina}}i]].  Each of these 13 major summits has at least {{convert|500|m|0|abbr=off|comma=5|sp=us}} of [[topographic prominence]].

The [[summit]] of a mountain or hill may be measured in three principal ways:
#The [[Elevation|topographic elevation]] of a summit measures the height of the summit above a [[Geoid|geodetic sea level]].<ref name=range>If the elevation or prominence of a summit is calculated as a range of values, the [[arithmetic mean]] is shown.</ref>  The [[#Highest major summits|first table]] below ranks the 13 major summits of Hawai{{okina}}i by topographic elevation.
#The [[topographic prominence]] of a summit is a measure of how high the summit rises above its surroundings.<ref name=prominence>The [[topographic prominence]] of a summit is the [[Elevation|topographic elevation]] difference between the summit and its [[Topographic prominence#Definitions|highest or key col to a higher summit]].  The summit may be near its key col or quite far away.  The key col for [[Denali]] in [[Alaska]] is the [[Isthmus of Rivas]] in [[Nicaragua]], {{convert|7642|km|0|abbr=off|comma=5|sp=us}} away.</ref><ref name=range/>  The [[#Most prominent summits|second table]] below ranks the 13 major summits of Hawai{{okina}}i by topographic prominence.
#The [[topographic isolation]] (or radius of dominance) of a summit measures how far the summit lies from its nearest point of equal elevation.<ref name=isolation>The [[topographic isolation]] of a summit is the [[great-circle distance]] to its nearest point of equal elevation.</ref>  The [[#Most isolated major summits|third table]] below ranks the 13 major summits of Hawai{{okina}}i by topographic isolation.

__TOC__{{clear}}

==Highest major summits==
{{GeoGroup|section=Highest major summits}}
Of the 13 major summits of Hawai{{okina}}i, Mauna Kea and Mauna Loa exceed {{convert|4000|m|0|abbr=off|comma=5|sp=us}} elevation, Haleakalā exceeds {{convert|3000|m|0|abbr=off|comma=5|sp=us}}, Hualalai exceeds {{convert|2000|m|0|abbr=off|comma=5|sp=us}}, and 11 peaks exceed {{convert|1000|m|0|abbr=off|comma=5|sp=us}} elevation.

Four of these peaks rise on the island of Hawai{{okina}}i, two on Maui, two on Kaua{{okina}}i, two on Moloka{{okina}}i, two on O{{okina}}ahu, and one on Lāna{{okina}}i.
{{clear}}
