{{Other uses|National Museum of Natural History (disambiguation)}} {{Infobox museum | name = National Museum of Natural History | native_name = Mużew Nazzjonali tal-Istorja Naturali | native_name_lang = mt | image = Natural History Museum Mdina (6810109710).jpg | imagesize = 300 | caption = The courtyard of [[Palazzo Vilhena]], which houses the museum | alt = | map_type = | map_relief = | map_size = | map_caption = | latitude = | longitude = | coordinates = {{coord|35.885|14.4037|display=inline,title}} | established = 22 June 1973 | dissolved = <!-- {{End date|YYYY|MM|DD|df=y}} --> | location = [[Palazzo Vilhena]], [[Mdina]], Malta | type = [[natural history museum]] | accreditation = | key_holdings = | collections = | collection_size = | visitors = | director = | president = | curator = | owner = | publictransit = | car_park = | network = | website = <!-- {{URL|example.com}} --> }}
The '''National Museum of Natural History''' ({{lang-mt|Mużew Nazzjonali tal-Istorja Naturali}}) is a [[natural history museum]] in the mediaeval walled city of [[Mdina]], Malta. It is housed in [[Palazzo Vilhena]], a [[French Baroque architecture|French Baroque]] palace rebuilt in 1726 by Grand Master [[Antonio Manoel de Vilhena]] to designs of [[Charles François de Mondion]]. The museum opened to the public in 1973, and is run by [[Heritage Malta]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://heritagemalta.org/museums-sites/national-museum-of-natural-history/ |title=National Museum of Natural History |publisher=Heritagemalta.org |date= |accessdate=2014-03-09}}</ref><ref name=old>[https://web.archive.org/web/20110726150827/http://www.heritagemalta.org/museums/naturalhistory/naturalhistoryhistory.html History] (old page). National Museum of Natural History. Archived 26 July 2011.</ref>
The museum gives the visitor an overview of Maltese ecosystems (both on ground and under water), focusing on endemic plants and bird of the Islands, such as the [[Maltese Centaury]] and [[Blue Rock Thrush]].
This museum display ranks a large variety of minerals, fossils, insects, reptiles, birds, mammals, fish and sections about [[Geology]] and [[Palaeontology]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.lifeshearwaterproject.org.mt/en/view.aspx?id=38 |title=Life Yelkouan Shearwater Project |publisher=Lifeshearwaterproject.org.mt |date= |accessdate=2010-11-13 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110722222434/http://www.lifeshearwaterproject.org.mt/en/view.aspx?id=38 |archivedate=2011-07-22 |df= }}</ref>
==Apollo 17 Goodwill Moon Rock== On Tuesday May 18, 2004, Malta’s Apollo 17 Goodwill [[Moon rock]] was stolen from the Museum.<ref>[http://www.thesun.co.uk/sol/homepage/news/article88898.ece "Malta’s Moon Rock Stolen: A TINY moon rock believed to be worth £2.8 million has been stolen from a museum in Malta, it emerged today."] The Sun (U.K), May 21, 2004.</ref> According to an Associated Press story the Moon rock has a value of 5 million dollars (U.S), making it one of the largest valued thefts in Malta's history.<ref>[https://www.usatoday.com/tech/news/2004-05-21-malta-moon-rock-stolen_x.htm " $5M moon rock stolen from Malta museum"] Associated Press Story appearing in USA Today, May 21, 2004.</ref> The Moon rock has not been recovered.<ref>Ex-NASA officer urges Malta amnesty to repossess moon rock. The Sunday Times (Malta), Herman Grech, May 22, 2004.</ref><ref>[http://www.collectspace.com/news/news-062902a.html Moon rock returns to Honduras]. CollectSpace.com. February 28th, 2004.</ref><ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/americas/3912829.stm American moon rock gifts vanish]. BBC, July 21, 2004.</ref><ref>[http://www.csmonitor.com/2004/0617/p14s02-stss.html In Malta, a moon-rock caper]. The [[Christian Science Monitor]], June 17, 2004.</ref><ref>[http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/life_and_style/article459076.ece?token=null&offset=0&page=1 Lost The Hottest Rocks on Earth]. [[The Times]], July 20th, 2004.</ref><ref>[http://www.chron.com/disp/story.mpl/nation/6993992.html Misplaced From Space: Every Nation Received a Moon Rock, Some Can't Find it]. [[The Houston Chronicle]], May 7, 2010.</ref><ref>[http://www.geotimes.org/nov04/trends.html In Search of the Goodwill Moon Rocks: A Personal Account] Geotimes Magazine, Joseph Gutheinz, November 2004.</ref>
