'''William Samuel Furneaux''' (2 June 1855, [[Devonport, Devon|Devonport]] – 1940) was a British science teacher and nature writer. He gained considerable fame in the 1890s and early twentieth century for his popular books dealing with butterflies, moths, pond animals, and plants found in the English countryside.<ref>{{cite journal|author=Ritchie, J.|title=Obituary: Mr. W. S. Furneaux|issue=145|page=886|date=8 June 1940|journal=Nature|doi=10.1038/145886b0}}</ref>

